ption of Covenant -- tAchaemenid Persian Concepts Pertaining to Covenant and Haggai, Zechariah, and Malachi -- tPart 4 Wisdom Literature -- tThe Psalms, Covenant, and the Persian Period -- tPoems, Prayers, and Promises The Psalms and Israel's Three Covenants -- t"When the Friendship of God Was upon My Tent" Covenant as Essential Background to Lament in the Wisdom Literature -- tQohelet and the Covenant: Some Preliminary Observations -- tPart 5 Chronicles, Ezr a, and Nehemiah -- tEzra 10:3: Solemn Oath? Renewed Covenant? New Covenant? -- tReenvisioning the Relationship: Covenant in Chronicles -- t"The Ark of the Covenant of the Lord" The Place of Covenant in the Chronicler's Theology -- tIndex of Authors -- tIndex of Scripture0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe 22 essays in this new and comprehensive study explore how notions of covenant, especially the Sinaitic covenant, flourished during the Neo-Babylonian, Persian, and early Hellenistic periods. Following the upheaval of the Davidic monarchy, the temple's destruction, the disenfranchisement of the Jerusalem priesthood, the deportation of Judeans to other lands, the struggles of Judeans who remained in the land, and the limited returns of some Judean groups from exile, the covenant motif proved to be an increasingly influential symbol in Judean intellectual life. The contributors to this volume, drawn from many different countries including Canada, Germany, Israel, South Africa, Switzerland, and the United States, document how Judean writers working within historiographic, Levitical, prophetic, priestly, and sapiential circles creatively reworked older notions of covenant to invent a new way of understanding this idea. These writers examine how new conceptions of the covenant made between YHWH and Israel at Mt. Sinai play a significant role in the process of early Jewish identity formation. Others focus on how transformations in the Abrahamic, Davidic, and Priestly covenants responded to cultural changes within Judean society, both in the homeland and in the diaspora. Cumulatively, the studies of biblical writings, from Genesis to Chronicles, demonstrate how Jewish literature in this period developed a striking diversity of ideas related to covenantal themes.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Aug 2021) 0aCovenant theologyxBiblical teaching. 0aJewsxHistoryyBabylonian captivity, 598-515 B.CxBiblical teaching. 0aJewsxHistoryyBabylonian captivity, 598-515 B.C.xBiblical teaching. 7aHISTORY / Ancient / General.2bisacsh1 aAchenbach, Reinhard, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAssis, Elie, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBautch, Richard J., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBautch, Richard J., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aBellinger Jr, W. H., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBolin, Thomas M., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDempsey, Carol J., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEdenburg, Cynthia, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGrant, Jamie A., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHibbard, J. Todd, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHieke, Thomas, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJonker, Louis C., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKessler, John, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKnoppers, Gary N., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aMitchell, Christine, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc